The paper deals with algorithms for sorting, max-finding, and selection, which are fundamental problems in computer science and are typically studied in the context of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The model of imprecise comparisons is inspired by human judgment and psychophysics, which are topics commonly studied in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the tradeoff between error and number of comparisons, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT) and computational complexity (cs.CC).
